// Regression test for a known compiler bug: a same-file class's bare
// `Foo(args)` constructor call is only resolved against its real
// declared constructor's parameter list when that list happens to match
// the class's *field* list (count and types) -- parser/type_system.py's
// "func_name in self.user_types" branch unconditionally re-validates the
// call against field order instead, as if the class had no explicit
// constructor at all (the branch meant for that case). Whenever an
// explicit constructor's params diverge from the fields even slightly,
// the wrong check fires:
//   - Zero declared constructor params (this file): "expected 1 args,
//     got 0" (Foo has exactly one field, so the implicit path expects
//     one positional field-initializer argument)
//   - A constructor taking fewer/more params than there are fields:
//     "expected <field count> args, got <param count>"
//   - A constructor param whose type differs from the field at the same
//     position: "arg 1 expected <field type>, got <param type>"
// `new Foo(args)` avoids this (uses the correct declared-constructor
// lookup) for a same-file class. Neither form avoids it for a class
// *imported from another module* with zero declared params, which fails
// differently -- see zero_arg_constructor_field_access_after_bare_call.fire
// for a separate, related symptom on such a class. Discovered while
// designing @firescript/std.text.StringBuilder, which sidesteps all of
// this by giving its constructor a real parameter that happens to match
// no field, and always being called cross-module (which routes through
// the correct constructor lookup regardless of this bug).
//
// Expected (correct) behavior once fixed: prints 42.
import @firescript/std.io.println;

class Foo {
    val: int32;

    fn Foo() {
        this.val = 42;
    }
}

f: Foo = Foo();
println(f.val);
